routing_summary.excerpt_summary: Section 9 defines mandatory-to-implement cipher suites, signature schemes, groups, and extensions for TLS 1.3, plus some protocol invariants that are stated to apply across TLS versions.

Temporal.explanation: Section 9 is largely about static requirements, not message ordering or timing.

ActorDirectionality.explanation: Requirements are mostly symmetric “TLS-compliant application” obligations, not subtle role inversions.

Scope.explanation: The normative scope (TLS 1.3 vs “earlier versions” vs “application profile may override”) is explicit and internally consistent.

Causal.explanation: No algorithmic steps here whose literal implementation would make the protocol unexecutable or insecure; it’s capability requirements, not procedures.

Quantitative.explanation: No tricky ranges, sizes, or counters in this section; cipher/group identifiers are consistent with earlier definitions.

Deontic.explanation: The MUST/SHOULD/MAY usage tightens requirements compared to RFC 8446 but does not conflict with earlier normative text in this draft.

Structural.explanation: No new ABNF/YANG/ASN.1; the referenced identifiers (cipher suites, extensions, SignatureScheme, NamedGroup) match the definitions in Sections 4 and B.

CrossRFC.explanation: References to RFC 6066, 7748, 8439, 5116, and GCM are aligned with how those RFCs define server_name, X25519, ChaCha20-Poly1305, and AES-GCM.

Terminology.explanation: Terms like “TLS-compliant application”, “mandatory-to-implement”, extension and cipher names are used consistently with the rest of the draft.

Boundary.explanation: Edge cases (e.g., PSK-only vs (EC)DHE, presence/absence of certain extensions) are constrained but not left undefined.
